I've just spent some time tracking down a scenario in which the initial value of an observable passed to `ToProperty()` is not immediately available and client code can see `default(T)` instead of the correct value.

Here is a repro:

```C#
namespace RxUIToPropertyRepro
{
    using System;
    using System.Reactive.Concurrency;
    using System.Reactive.Linq;
    using NUnit.Framework;
    using ReactiveUI;

    [TestFixture]
    public class Repro
    {
        [Test]
        public void immediate_access_when_using_to_property()
        {
            var sut = new ToPropertyScenario(328);
            Assert.AreEqual(328, sut.Value);
        }

        [Test]
        public void immediate_access_via_current_thread_scheduler_when_using_to_property()
        {
            CurrentThreadScheduler.Instance.Schedule(() =>
            {
                var sut = new ToPropertyScenario(328);
                Assert.AreEqual(328, sut.Value);
            });
        }

        [Test]
        public void immediate_access_via_immediate_scheduler_when_using_to_property()
        {
            ImmediateScheduler.Instance.Schedule(() =>
            {
                var sut = new ToPropertyScenario(328);
                Assert.AreEqual(328, sut.Value);
            });
        }

        [Test]
        public void immediate_access_when_using_private_field()
        {
            var sut = new PrivateFieldScenario(328);
            Assert.AreEqual(328, sut.Value);
        }

        [Test]
        public void immediate_access_via_current_thread_scheduler_when_using_private_field()
        {
            CurrentThreadScheduler.Instance.Schedule(() =>
            {
                var sut = new PrivateFieldScenario(328);
                Assert.AreEqual(328, sut.Value);
            });
        }
    }

    public class ToPropertyScenario : ReactiveObject
    {
        private readonly ObservableAsPropertyHelper<int> value;

        public ToPropertyScenario(int initialValue = default(int))
        {
            this.value = Observable.Return(initialValue)
                .ToProperty(this, x => x.Value);
        }

        public int Value
        {
            get { return this.value.Value; }
        }
    }

    public class PrivateFieldScenario : ReactiveObject
    {
        private int value;

        public PrivateFieldScenario(int initialValue = default(int))
        {
            Observable.Return(initialValue)
                .Subscribe(x => this.Value = x);
        }

        public int Value
        {
            get { return this.value; }
            private set { this.RaiseAndSetIfChanged(ref this.value, value); }
        }
    }
}
```
Of these tests, only one fails: `immediate_access_via_current_thread_scheduler_when_using_to_property`. It seems that because the client code is executing inside a scheduled message, the value of the property is not available until later (i.e. when the scheduler is freed up to determine it). This is common when the code is executing as the result of a reactive command, for example.

This does not align with my expectations of how `ToProperty()` should work, nor does it seem to align with [the docs](https://github.com/reactiveui/ReactiveUI/blob/docs/docs/basics/to-property.md):

> It's important to know the semantics of `ToProperty` - you should conceptualize this method as similar to `Subscribe`: it causes the Observable to be evaluated, just like `foreach` causes Enumerables to be evaluated.

There are several workarounds that I know of, some of which are demonstrated in tests above:

1. Use a `private` field and `Subscribe` (see tests).
2. Use the immediate scheduler for the call to `ToProperty()` (see tests)
3. Specify the immediate scheduler in the call to `ToProperty()`
4. Specify the initial value in the call to `ToProperty()`, even though the observable is cold and has an initial value in it

None of these options quite fits my mental model of how `ToProperty()` should be working. Is my understanding of `ToProperty()` wrong, or is there an implementation problem here?

